  "What does FOIL stand for?": "",
  "Find, Organize, Identify, List": "",
  "First, Outer, Inner, Last": "",
  "First, Only, Inner, Least": "",
  "Factor, Order, Inverse, Last": "",
  "FOIL stands for First, Outer, Inner, Last -- it describes the order in which you multiply the terms of two binomials: (a + b)(c + d).": "",
  "What is the 'distributive property' as it applies to polynomial multiplication?": "",
  "Every term in one polynomial must be multiplied by every term in the other polynomial": "",
  "You only multiply the first terms of each polynomial": "",
  "You add corresponding terms from each polynomial": "",
  "You divide each term by the leading coefficient": "",
  "The distributive property states that a(b + c) = ab + ac. When multiplying polynomials, each term in the first polynomial must be multiplied by each term in the second polynomial.": "",
  "What is the 'difference of squares' pattern?": "",
  "(a − b)² = a² − b²": "",
  "(a + b)² = a² + 2ab + b²": "",
  "a² − b² = (a − b)²": "",
  "(a + b)(a − b) = a² − b²": "",
  "The difference of squares is the identity (a + b)(a − b) = a² − b². The middle terms cancel because the outer and inner products are equal in magnitude but opposite in sign.": "",
  "What is a 'perfect square trinomial'?": "",
  "A trinomial that can only be factored by grouping": "",
  "Any trinomial with degree 3": "",
  "Any trinomial where all coefficients are perfect squares": "",
  "A trinomial that results from squaring a binomial, such as a² + 2ab + b² or a² − 2ab + b²": "",
  "A perfect square trinomial has the form a² + 2ab + b² = (a + b)² or a² − 2ab + b² = (a − b)². The middle term is always twice the product of the square roots of the first and last terms.": "",
  "When multiplying polynomials, the degree of the product equals:": "",
  "The difference of the degrees of the factors": "",
