  "Adding more terms to the polynomial": "",
  "Finding the factors of a polynomial": "",
  "Increasing the degree of the polynomial": "",
  "Expanding means multiplying out a factored form and writing the result as a sum of individual terms. For example, expanding (x + 2)(x + 3) gives x² + 5x + 6.": "",
  "What is the 'area model' (or box method) for polynomial multiplication?": "",
  "A visual grid where each term of one polynomial is placed along one side and each term of the other along the adjacent side, with products in each cell": "",
  "Drawing each polynomial term on a number line and combining their values by measuring the total distance from the origin": "",
  "A graphical method limited to multiplying linear polynomials where you plot both lines and find the intersection area": "",
  "Finding the area underneath the polynomial curve by summing the values at each integer point to get the expanded product": "",
  "The area model (box method) organizes multiplication into a grid. Each term of one factor labels a row, each term of the other labels a column, and each cell contains the product of its row and column terms.": "",
  "What does 'like terms' mean when simplifying after multiplication?": "",
  "Terms that were produced during the same step of the FOIL method, meaning they came from the same pair of multiplied binomial terms": "",
  "Terms with the same variable(s) raised to the same power(s) that can be combined by adding coefficients": "",
  "Any two terms that appear next to each other in the expanded expression, regardless of their variable parts or exponents": "",
  "Terms that share the same numerical coefficient, which means they can always be grouped and factored out together": "",
  "After multiplying polynomials, you combine like terms -- those with identical variable parts (same variables raised to the same powers) -- by adding their coefficients.": "",
